37:28.713 --> 37:30.515 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Virginia, and the list goes on
and on and
on.

37:30.548 --> 37:35.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there's obviously a lot of
factors why
white men might not want to vote
for Hillary

37:35.353 --> 37:39.591 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Clinton in the general election,
also in the
primaries, but gender is
obviously sort of

37:39.624 --> 37:41.926 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
an underlying current in this
election.

37:41.960 --> 37:45.363 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: In your piece,
you introduced
me to a term I had never heard
about before.

37:45.396 --> 37:47.665 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's called ambivalent sexism.

37:47.699 --> 37:49.501 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
What is that?

37:49.534 --> 37:53.872 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANIEL BUSH: So, researchers who
study these
issues, who study bias and
stereotyping, for

37:53.905 --> 37:57.775 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
a long time thought that
stereotyping was
basically uniformly negative.

37:57.809 --> 38:04.782 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But what researchers who focus
on gender specifically
in the 1990s and on have
realized is that

38:04.816 --> 38:06.751 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
gender bias takes different
forms.

38:06.784 --> 38:12.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, there's what they call
hostile sexism,
sort of overtly negative views
of women, what

38:12.323 --> 38:14.759 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we typically associate with
gender discrimination,
right?

38:14.792 --> 38:20.131 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Then there's also ambivalent or
benevolent
sexism, which, from a male point
of view,

38:20.165 --> 38:24.402 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
encourages men to be supportive
of women who
are in traditional roles,
traditional gender

38:24.435 --> 38:29.440 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
roles, but when women step out
of that, when
they seek power, when they seek
to enter male-dominated

38:29.474 --> 38:31.509 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
fields, men tend to look at them
worse.

38:31.543 --> 38:33.912 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And obviously we're seeing that
play out with
Hillary Clinton.

38:33.945 --> 38:37.582 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: In piece, you
talked with
a lot of white male voters in
Ohio and Pennsylvania.

38:37.615 --> 38:41.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Obviously, when someone is
asked, they're
going to say, I'm not a sexist,
I don't have

38:41.786 --> 38:43.154 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
those feelings.

38:43.188 --> 38:45.590 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, how did you see this play
out in the men
that you talked to?

38:45.623 --> 38:49.994 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANIEL BUSH: So, I talked to a
lot of voters
who said, yes, I feel
comfortable voting for

38:50.028 --> 38:52.463 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a woman, but just not Hillary
Clinton.

38:52.497 --> 38:54.199 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
She's not the right one.

38:54.232 --> 38:58.269 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then they went on to list a
number of
reasons: She's too shrill, she's
too loud,

38:58.303 --> 38:59.971 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
she's not trustworthy.

39:00.004 --> 39:03.541 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And while they may feel that
about Clinton,
sort of generally speaking, on a
personal

39:03.575 --> 39:08.079 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
level, without realizing that it
has to do
with gender, all of the
signifiers that they

39:08.112 --> 39:14.385 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
used to describe a woman in
power or running
for a top position in government
sort of come

39:14.419 --> 39:20.024 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
into play and are connected to
the way that
researchers look at gender bias
and discrimination.

39:20.058 --> 39:23.795 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: How do we know
with some
of the other men that you talked
to, or just

39:23.828 --> 39:29.067 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
men more broadly, that their
beef with Hillary
Clinton might be about her
policies or her

39:29.100 --> 39:30.602 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
positions?

39:30.635 --> 39:32.770 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, how do we know that it's
overtly about
the fact that she's a woman?

39:32.804 --> 39:39.143 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANIEL BUSH: On an individual,
case-by-case
basis, it's difficult to say,
yes, this voter

39:39.177 --> 39:43.548 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in particular doesn't like
Hillary Clinton
only because she is a woman.

39:43.581 --> 39:47.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, of course, there are
millions of voters
across the country, in the
primaries, and

39:47.452 --> 39:51.389 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there will be in the general,
who have legitimate
policy disagreements, right,
with Clinton,

39:51.422 --> 39:54.592 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
whether it's about health care,
whether it's
about taxes, and so on.

39:54.626 --> 39:58.162 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But when you really start
talking to men -- and
in this story in particular, we
were looking

39:58.196 --> 40:02.934 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at white men -- you see that
gender is an
underlying sort of current in
the way that

40:02.967 --> 40:04.702 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
they think about Hillary
Clinton.

40:04.736 --> 40:07.872 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, going
forward, we have
now an election with Trump
against Hillary.

40:07.905 --> 40:10.842 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
How do you foresee this
particular conversation
playing out?

40:10.875 --> 40:15.546 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANIEL BUSH: The people that I
spoke to for
this piece compared it a little
bit to the

40:15.580 --> 40:20.051 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
change in dialogue on race
relations after
President Obama was elected.

40:20.084 --> 40:25.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we might see a similar thing
play out
here where, whether Clinton wins
or loses,

40:25.723 --> 40:30.061 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there's going to be sort of a
more -- a greater
public consciousness, right,
about gender,

40:30.094 --> 40:34.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about gender roles, about the
way that men
and women hold power in the
country.

40:34.699 --> 40:35.667 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And it might be ugly.

40:35.700 --> 40:37.001 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It might be divisive.

40:37.035 --> 40:39.370 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We can certainly expect that in
the general
election campaign.

40:39.404 --> 40:42.740 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, hopefully, at least it will
get people
talking about it and thinking
about it as

40:42.774 --> 40:44.275 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
well.

40:44.309 --> 40:45.576 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right, the
"NewsHour"'s
Daniel Bush, thanks for this.

40:45.610 --> 40:46.577 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Great reporting.

40:46.611 --> 40:48.379 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DANIEL BUSH: Thanks for having
me.

40:48.413 --> 40:51.816 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: For more on
the gender gap
and the future of the Democratic
Party, we

40:51.849 --> 40:54.852 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
go back to Gwen and Judy in
Philadelphia.

40:54.886 --> 40:58.556 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Thank you, Hari.

40:58.589 --> 41:03.094 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we pick up on the challenges
Hillary Clinton
faces, especially with white
male voters in

41:03.127 --> 41:05.330 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
this election, with Richard
Trumka.

41:05.363 --> 41:06.998 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He's the president of the
AFL-CIO.

41:07.031 --> 41:11.969 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's the largest organization of
labor unions
in the country.

41:12.003 --> 41:14.205 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And Senator Cory Booker of New
Jersey.

41:14.238 --> 41:15.973 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we welcome both of you to
the program.

41:16.007 --> 41:18.042 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Rich Trumka, let me start with
you.

41:18.076 --> 41:22.180 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Pick up on what you just heard
from our reporter
Dan Bush.

41:22.213 --> 41:26.884 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What do you hear, what do you
know about your
rank-and-file union members who
are hearing

41:26.918 --> 41:31.823 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Donald Trump saying, "I will be
your voice,
if you feel forgotten, I will be
your voice,"

41:31.856 --> 41:37.829 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
