opportunity overseas.

47:09.827 --> 47:12.730 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, this has got to be an
election where we
talk to people's interests.

47:12.763 --> 47:17.535 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what I don't want to see my
party do is
to begin to talk down towards
white men, as

47:17.568 --> 47:21.005 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
if their concerns are not
legitimate and that
we shouldn't be listening to a
lot of their

47:21.038 --> 47:22.540 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
aspirations and hopes as well.

47:22.573 --> 47:24.742 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Senator Booker, you
and I have
talked about this lot.

47:24.775 --> 47:29.613 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Four years -- eight years ago,
we saw the
breakthrough with President
Obama.

47:29.647 --> 47:35.252 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Americans had to adjust
their thinking
in order to elect the first
black president.

47:35.286 --> 47:37.521 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What is necessary for Americans
to elect the
first woman president?

47:37.555 --> 47:38.522 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
More or less difficult?

47:38.556 --> 47:40.324 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

47:40.357 --> 47:43.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CORY BOOKER: Well, I think that
we need to
have an honest conversation in
this country.

47:43.661 --> 47:48.299 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And this idea that somehow we're
beyond sexism,
beyond racism is just wrong.

47:48.332 --> 47:52.603 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this is where having an
honest conversation
with white men about their
issues and their

47:52.636 --> 47:55.940 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
concerns, and having honest
conversations
about the experiences that
African-Americans

47:55.973 --> 47:59.477 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are still having, despite who's
the president
of the United States, in the
criminal justice

47:59.510 --> 48:04.348 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
system that we see in
sentencing, we see in
policing and a lot of these
issues.

48:04.381 --> 48:06.117 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Gender bias is real.

48:06.150 --> 48:09.620 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I was an early Obama supporter,
and I was
even shocked at the way the
media treated

48:09.653 --> 48:12.656 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
President Obama vs. how they
treated Secretary
Clinton.

48:12.690 --> 48:17.161 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Questions that were asked about,
what is wearing,
how much does she weigh, about
her hair were

48:17.194 --> 48:18.763 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
never ascribed to the president.

48:18.796 --> 48:20.531 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We live in a gender-biased
world.

48:20.564 --> 48:25.402 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I see -- saw it growing up with
a mom who
was one of first people -- women
to make high

48:25.436 --> 48:30.941 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
